I can't reproduce from scratch again right now (a) no time (b) I'm not installing 2.10 again, then  have to remove and reinstall 2.8. If it helps, here is a corrupted image. You can't change any properties etc. I don't have the uncorrupted version, I didn't know that Id need it!

I'm finding @Jehan 's comments quite concerning. 'None of none of the developers use Windows". In that case (and I though many developers were involved) it means that although you provide a Windows version of GIMP, it has never been tested? Surely that's irresponsible and has resulted in corruption of a fair number of my image files with now no chance of getting back to the originals. that's not even a 'beta' release'.

I also think you are focused on the wrong thing - the terminology. Because teh key thing is that GIMP is changing something that is making WINDOWS refuse to allow something else to be subsequently changed.I have described the steps that result in the corrupted files. You need only take one of those scenarios. But yes, a tag (which you can think of as a label, and each file in Windows can have multiple tags) is part of metadata, and metadata is part of the properties of a file. I thought 'file properties' was  a common term in all IT, or was when I worked in IT from 1970-2014, on at least 30 distinct OS (and many versions of those), maybe it changed since. For example, file size is a file property, but not one you can change except by changing the content. As I understand it, EXIF data is a type of metadata that is stored on the image file by the camera device. Some EXIF data is stored in metadata fields which are also used by Windows OS and all EXIF data can be viewed and mostly edited in Windows. 'File attributes' is a phrase often used to describe flag type metadata such as 'hidden' or 'read only' I haven't experimented with that and GIMP as there is no need.

